    en: "A general contractor completed a $280,000 commercial office renovation in Rochester. The owner approved the final invoice of $62,000 but delayed payment for 45 days past the 30-day deadline. Counsel for the contractor sent a written demand citing GBL 756-a and the 1-percent-per-month interest accrual. The owner's response objected to $8,000 worth of work but more than 12 business days after the original invoice — untimely under the Act. The contractor filed suit in Monroe County Supreme Court for the $62,000 plus interest (approximately $930 at 1.5 months) plus attorney's fees. The contractor simultaneously filed a mechanics lien. At settlement conference, the owner paid $63,200 covering the invoice and statutory interest, plus $7,800 in attorney's fees under GBL 756-c. Work was never suspended because payment arrived before the 10-day suspension notice period completed. Subcontractors were paid by the contractor within 7 days of receipt per the Act."
